<DOC><DOCNO> AP890824-0109 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 1432EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Soviet     08-24 0245</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Poland-Soviet,0251</SECOND><HEAD>Soviet Council Expresses Hope For Stable Ties With Poland</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Soviet Council of Ministers congratulatedPoland's new non-Communist prime minister Thursday and expressedhope his election would not damage relations between the countries.   Tadeusz Mazowiecki, a veteran Solidarity activist, was electedprime minister earlier in the day by the Sejm, the lower house ofPoland's National Assembly. The historic vote made him the firstnon-Communist chief of government in the East bloc.   Within hours, the Council of Ministers, or Soviet cabinet, sentMazowiecki a telegram of ``friendly congratulations'' that also wascarried by the official Soviet news agency Tass.   ``We express the certainty that the traditional relations offriendship and all around cooperation between the Soviet Union andPoland will continue developing in the basis of sovereign equalityand respect, mutual benefit and mutual responsibility,'' the Councilof Ministers said.   An interview with Mazowiecki also was printed Thursday in theSoviet government's evening newspaper, Izvestia. The new Polishleader was quoted as saying his government would be open to all,including the Polish Communist Party, but that the time was clearlypast ``when only one camp could form the government.''   At a regular news briefing, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesmanYuri A. Gremitskikh also reacted to Mazowiecki's election withequanimity.   ``The Soviet side takes the decision into account and we shallregard comrade Mazowiecki as our partner in the relations that linkour two countries,'' he said.</TEXT></DOC>